==English==

===Etymology===
Earlier {{term|seise|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|seisen|lang=enm}}, {{term|sesen|lang=enm}}, {{term|saisen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|seisir||to take possession of; invest (person, court)|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{term|sacīre||to lay claim to, appropriate|lang=la}} (8th century) in the phrase {{term||ad propriam sacire}}, from Old Low {{etyl|frk|en}} {{term/t|frk|*sakjan||to sue, bring legal action}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*sakjaną}}, {{term/t|gem-pro|*sakōną}} (compare {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|sacian||to strive, brawl|lang=ang}}), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*sakaną}} (compare {{etyl|osx|-}} {{term|sakan||to accuse|lang=osx}}, {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|sahhan||to bicker, quarrel, rebuke|lang=goh}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} ''[[sacan]]'' 'to quarrel, claim by law, accuse').<ref>C.T. Onions, ed., Oxford Dictionary of English Etymology, s.v. "seize" (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1996), 807.</ref>  See [[sake]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|sēz}}, {{IPA|/siːz/}}
* {{audio|en-us-seize.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{homophones|lang=en|seas|sees}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|seiz|ing}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to deliberately take hold of; to [[grab]] or [[capture]]
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to take advantage of (an [[opportunity]] or [[circumstance]])
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to take possession of (by force, law etc.)
#: ''to seize smuggled goods''
#: ''to seize a ship after libeling''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to have a sudden and powerful effect upon
#: ''a panic seized the crowd''
#: ''a fever seized him''
# {{context|transitive|nautical|lang=en}} to [[bind]], [[lash]] or make [[fast]], with several turns of small rope, cord, or small line
#: ''to seize two fish-hooks back to back''
#: ''to seize or stop one rope on to another''
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} to [[fasten]], [[fix]]
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} to lay hold in [[seizure]], by hands or claws (+ {{term|on|lang=en}} or {{term|upon|lang=en}})
#: ''to seize on the neck of a horse''
#: ''The text which had seized upon his heart with such comfort and strength abode upon him for more than a year.'' (''Southey'', Bunyan, p. 21)
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} to have a [[seizure]]
#* '''2012''', Daniel M. Avery, ''Tales of a Country Obstetrician''
#*: Nearing what she thought was a climax, he started '''seizing''' and fell off her. Later, realizing he was dead, she became alarmed and dragged the body to his vehicle to make it look like he had died in his truck.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} to [[bind]] or [[lock]] in position [[immovably]]; see also '''[[seize up]]'''
#: ''Rust caused the engine to '''seize''', never to run again.''

